Wheelmade Nile silt pottery cup with straight sides, simple direct rim and recessed spot base. Well-sorted eggshell fabric, but heavy in weight. Cup is covered in red slip interior and exterior. description.value: Travertine amphora; rim thickened with rounded exterior; short cylindrical neck; body with rounded shoulder and slightly curved walls; disc base; two horizontal loop handles on shoulders, drilled through from underside; black painted decoration comprising double framed row of petals around upper neck and semi-circular floral garland on shoulder; paint preserved on one side only; vessel partially reconstructed and chips missing from rim; drilled and ground.  Travertine amphora; long cylindrical neck with carved stepped rim and round mouth; shallow incision at neck to body join; elongated ovoid body with protrusion at base for attachment to foot (missing); two vertical loop handles below shoulder; loop interiors drilled; ground and polished; the neck and at least one of the handles were formed from separate pieces of stone.

description.value:
Black pottery necked jar with a wide mouth, short neck and low shoulder, with a globular body and rounded base. The jar is handmade in a deoxidised fabric with much straw, Adams Ware H11, and has several firing stains. There is impressed decoration on shoulder:
Single row of impressed oval dots diagonally laid at the top of the shoulder, all the way around the neck. Below, parallel lines of rectangular impressed dots diagonal to the left at a slight angle, 8-10 each. Below this, further rectangular impressed dots at a less steep angle, c. 9 each. These are not constant but rather are broken by 7 gaps, which have three lines making a thin triangle shape.

description.value: Vase with ovoid body: with a rounded base, sloping shoulders, and a tapering cylindrical neck has a body fabric of dark-blue glass now completely opaque. On the rim and directly below it are prefabricated bands of opaque white and black chevrons in relief. Simple festoons in the traditional white, yellow, and light blue decorate the balance of the neck. These colours are repeated in the clustered festoons of the upper body and appear again in the inverted festoons of the lower body. Between these festoons is a register of chevrons in combinations of white and turquoise-blue.    The decorations described are conventional but in addition there are details which are probably unique in glass vessels, ones which identify this as a figure vase. On the body female breasts are indicated by two discs or buttons, prefabricated and impressed, having blue fields, yellow centres, and encircled by white and black bands. On the neck at the centre of the lower prefabricated band, directly centred over the two breasts are the remains of an opaque yellow detail applied separately and now largely lost. This can only have been a conventionalized representation of a face frontal. The applied face on the neck almost completely lost. Much of the surface is filmed white.

description.value: Handleless ovoid pottery jar with a rounded base and a short everted neck (2.5cm high); ridged body, coil-built and finished on wheel. The shoulder is decorated with three representations of eyes in the same thin brown paint, with a thick red outline added around the eyeball. description.value: Fragmentary jar with pointed base: the wreck of a fine piece. The shape, directly copied from pottery wine jars, was popular late in the Eighteenth Dynasty. The opaque light turquoise-blue field is decorated in a flowing festoon pattern in white and yellow bordered at its upper level with a white and a yellow thread. Both the shoulder and the rim are encircled with  a  prefabricated twisted cord in yellow and black (?). The original surface was probably glossy. On the neck a chevron pattern  in opaque white and yellow. The sole remaining handle is in opaque black glass overlaid with threads of opaque white and yellow. The body is very incompletely preserved.
